     Pants him. Pants him.      
    Pants him. Pants him...     

14:02.809 --> 14:04.376
        Hey, Sam.               

14:06.212 --> 14:08.013
Hey, Sam, I hope                
you're not still mad at me      

14:08.081 --> 14:09.515
about that haircut thing.       

14:09.582 --> 14:11.150
     Nice hat, by the way.      

14:11.217 --> 14:14.520
You know, my cousin Elmore had  
a hunting cap just like that.   

14:14.587 --> 14:16.622
     Of course he decorated     
     it with deer antlers.      

14:16.690 --> 14:17.890
     Big mistake.               

14:21.361 --> 14:24.296
            Sam... why aren't   
              you talking to me?

14:24.364 --> 14:26.198
                        Sam?    

14:26.266 --> 14:27.366
                          CLIFF:
                          Woody?

14:27.434 --> 14:29.268
                    I think he's
                ignoring you.   

14:30.737 --> 14:33.072
              Is that true, Sam?

14:33.139 --> 14:36.775
You know for a minute there     
I thought I heard something.    

14:36.843 --> 14:40.946
A little tiny voice of          
a nothing jerk bartender.       

14:42.816 --> 14:44.516
                      Me?       

14:44.584 --> 14:46.251
I think I was wrong.            

14:46.319 --> 14:49.254
I think it was just a tiny      
little insignificant bug.       

14:51.324 --> 14:52.725
            Well, that's very   
                      funny Sam,

14:52.792 --> 14:56.195
      but it's not a tiny little
              insignificant bug.

14:56.262 --> 14:59.098
             It's your assistant
     bartender-- good old Woody.

15:04.237 --> 15:05.671
            I think I got it.   

15:07.640 --> 15:10.376
      I can't believe it.       

15:10.443 --> 15:12.344
    I'm being shunned.          

15:13.813 --> 15:16.015
Just like back in Hanover.      

15:16.082 --> 15:19.418
Just like with the Amish.       

15:19.486 --> 15:21.053
                        NORM:   
                        Wood?   

15:21.121 --> 15:24.189
      Who, uh, who shunned      
      you back in Hanover?      

15:24.257 --> 15:27.126
  The Amish. Weren't you here   
         for this part?         

15:29.462 --> 15:32.164
Please, miss,                   
can I just have my beer?        

15:32.232 --> 15:36.201
            All right. I'm gonna
    give you one last chance,   
            and this is a gimme.

15:36.269 --> 15:40.706
  What was the year of Elvis'   
     big comeback special?      

15:40.774 --> 15:42.341
              '72.              

15:42.409 --> 15:44.943
        You're pathetic.        

15:45.011 --> 15:46.745
Hey, I paid for that beer.      

15:46.813 --> 15:48.981
     Well, then I guess you     
 just should have studied, huh? 

15:50.417 --> 15:52.851
    I hope we weren't           
    too hard on Fras.           

15:52.919 --> 15:55.287
    Well, his being ridiculed   
        in here is one thing,   

15:55.355 --> 15:57.923
    but out in public, that's   
          got to be humiliating.

15:57.991 --> 15:59.158
I know what you're saying.      
                        Yeah.   

15:59.225 --> 16:00.759
You know,                       
when I was a kid,               

16:00.827 --> 16:02.728
I was the first one             
in my class to...               

16:02.796 --> 16:05.431
you know, develop breasts.      

16:06.966 --> 16:08.767
 They teased me the whole year. 

16:08.835 --> 16:10.336
    Oh, yeah, me, too.          

16:14.174 --> 16:17.643
Yeah, I took my fair share      
of ribbing back in Hanover.     

16:17.711 --> 16:18.711
                        Yeah?   

16:18.778 --> 16:21.146
"Little Einstein"               
they called me.                 

16:23.817 --> 16:25.918
"Mr. Smarty Pants."             

16:25.985 --> 16:27.753
    "Brainiac."                 

16:27.821 --> 16:30.456
Yep. I've heard 'em all.        

16:30.523 --> 16:32.891
      Before I die, I got       
    to see that town.           

16:38.531 --> 16:39.999
So what about you, Cliff?       

16:40.066 --> 16:41.700
                     Well, sorry
            I can't help you.   

16:41.768 --> 16:42.901
                Happy childhood.

16:42.969 --> 16:44.837
      Well-adjusted, well-liked.

16:44.904 --> 16:46.171
            Class valedictorian.

16:46.239 --> 16:47.940
                    I'd show you
                    my yearbook,

16:48.008 --> 16:49.708
but Ma apparently thought       

16:49.776 --> 16:51.477
    some of the inscriptions    
        were off-color.         

16:52.712 --> 16:55.781
          So she made me eat it.

16:55.849 --> 16:59.151
         Nope. No problems here.

17:02.155 --> 17:03.389
                      Hey, Fras.

17:03.456 --> 17:05.023
      Don't "Hey Fras" me.      

17:05.090 --> 17:06.759
    After the way you people    
         behaved today,         

17:06.826 --> 17:08.861
     you're lucky I am even     
        speaking to you.        

17:08.928 --> 17:11.363
How dare you treat me like that 
    in front of my patients!    

17:11.431 --> 17:14.800
    I have been your friend,    
        your confidante,        

17:14.867 --> 17:18.971
your unpaid therapist           
for years.                      

17:19.039 --> 17:20.772
            And how do you show 
              your gratitude?   

17:20.839 --> 17:22.340
             By humiliating me, 
             by making me a...  

17:22.409 --> 17:23.876
             a laughingstock.   

17:23.943 --> 17:26.912
    Come on, Fras, those guys   
    were scared stiff of you.   

17:26.980 --> 17:29.081
         That's why they weren't
            getting anywhere.   

17:29.149 --> 17:31.817
    We were just trying to bring
    you down a peg, you know?   

17:31.885 --> 17:34.119
Yeah, come on, Fras,            
 you've got to admit, uh,       

17:34.187 --> 17:36.488
sometimes you get up            
on that high horse of yours.    

17:36.556 --> 17:38.991
High horse?!                    
Well, I never.                  

17:42.062 --> 17:44.530
                 Oh, God,       
            Lilith was right.   

17:44.597 --> 17:45.764
            Bringing those      
            patients here       

17:45.832 --> 17:48.000
        was the worst thing I've
        ever done in my life.   

17:48.068 --> 17:51.637
     This entire affair has been
        an unmitigated disaster.

17:51.705 --> 17:53.305
Hey look, there's Dr. Crane.    

17:53.373 --> 17:54.506
                      Dr. Crane.

17:54.574 --> 17:56.742
         We figured out what you
            were doing today,   

17:56.810 --> 17:58.444
                     and thanks.

17:58.511 --> 18:00.212
            I beg your pardon?  

18:00.280 --> 18:01.313
                  Well, you were
                      letting us

18:01.381 --> 18:03.115
            do all that stuff   
            to you just so we   

18:03.183 --> 18:04.216
            could feel better   
                about ourselves.

18:04.284 --> 18:05.684
          What a guy.           

18:05.752 --> 18:07.219
    You know, you've really     
          got to care           

18:07.287 --> 18:08.487
        to go that far.         

18:08.555 --> 18:11.890
              How about that.   

18:11.958 --> 18:14.293
        They <i>have</i>               
     figured it out.            

18:14.361 --> 18:16.395
            (chuckles)          

18:16.463 --> 18:18.330
                This is the best
              group we ever had.

18:18.398 --> 18:19.531
          (laughing):           
         Yeah, well...          

18:19.599 --> 18:21.533
                 (mumbling):    
                  ...genius.    
     Oh, well,                  

18:21.601 --> 18:22.634
    I wouldn't really           
     say "genius," Lester.      

18:22.702 --> 18:23.902
That is what you said, isn't it?

18:25.605 --> 18:27.473
     Gentlemen, good night.     

18:27.540 --> 18:29.008
Good night.                     
                      Thank you,
                      Dr. Crane.

18:29.075 --> 18:32.077
You've all made wonderful       
        progress today.         

18:32.145 --> 18:35.014
                      Thank you,
                      Dr. Crane.
      Thank you very much.      

18:35.081 --> 18:36.749
              You know, maybe in
                a hundred years,

18:36.816 --> 18:39.084
              they'll be able to
            walk through a mall.

18:39.152 --> 18:40.486
                        FRASIER:
                            Bye.

18:40.553 --> 18:44.523
              So, you all caught
                a little glimpse

18:44.591 --> 18:47.226
                into the life of
                Frasier Crane...

18:47.293 --> 18:49.661
                      M.D., PhD.

18:49.729 --> 18:52.631
             Try not to think of
              me any differently

18:52.699 --> 18:55.434
                 now that you've
    witnessed my unique gift.   

18:55.502 --> 18:57.836
      You see, although I wasn't
    completely aware of it,     

18:57.904 --> 19:00.606
              I intuited        
        what those men needed   

19:00.674 --> 19:02.741
        and I gave it to them,  
    freely and of myself...     

19:02.809 --> 19:05.911
for I am a healer.              

19:05.979 --> 19:08.681
That is what I do.              

19:09.783 --> 19:12.551
         And we                 
     are pantsers.              

19:12.619 --> 19:14.720
                         That is
                     what <i>we</i> do.

19:14.788 --> 19:16.221
            Oh, no.             

19:16.289 --> 19:17.222
     No, fellas, not again.     

19:17.290 --> 19:19.425
                No, no, these   
                  are new pants!

19:35.742 --> 19:39.011
                Sam, I've really
                 enjoyed the way

19:39.079 --> 19:43.082
          you've been pretending
    I'm a bug and everything.   

19:43.149 --> 19:45.651
                But I'm not a   
                 bug; I'm Woody.

19:55.161 --> 19:57.496
         Sam, where I come from,
            we have a saying,   

19:57.564 --> 19:59.131
            "An eye for an eye."

19:59.199 --> 20:01.200
                The point being,
                      of course,

20:01.267 --> 20:02.634
                 you're supposed
            to shave my head,   

20:02.702 --> 20:04.203
        not shave out my eye.   

20:05.305 --> 20:07.006
        (buzzing)               

20:07.073 --> 20:08.507
    Oh, man.                    

20:08.575 --> 20:09.842
This is stupid.                 
         (buzzing stops)        

20:09.909 --> 20:11.276
I don't want                    
to cut your hair.               

20:11.344 --> 20:12.311
                      You don't?

20:12.379 --> 20:13.946
    No.                         

20:14.014 --> 20:16.148
              So you forgive me?

20:16.216 --> 20:18.083
 Yeah, let's just just forget   
    about the whole thing,      

20:18.151 --> 20:19.718
all right?                      

20:19.786 --> 20:23.022
                 That... that is
                real noble, Sam.

20:23.089 --> 20:26.258
I mean, here I wrecked          
your hair,                      

20:26.326 --> 20:28.293
your... your beautiful,         
beautiful hair,                 

20:28.361 --> 20:31.163
the one thing you care most     
about in the whole world,       

20:31.231 --> 20:33.065
and yet, you're willing         
to forgive me.                  

20:33.133 --> 20:34.600
I mean, you know,               

20:34.668 --> 20:36.368
every time you look             
in the mirror,                  

20:36.436 --> 20:38.437
you're gonna be reminded        
of what I did to you,           

20:38.505 --> 20:41.273
and yet, you say                
it's okay.                      

20:41.341 --> 20:43.375
I have never                    
liked you more                  

20:43.443 --> 20:46.178
than I do                       
right now, Sam...               

20:46.246 --> 20:48.480
ridiculous haircut              
and all.                        

20:50.583 --> 20:53.919
              Woody, come in the
                 office with me,

20:53.987 --> 20:55.354
              just for a second.

20:55.422 --> 20:57.022
Sure, why?                      

20:57.090 --> 20:58.323
        No reason.              

20:58.391 --> 21:01.160
        (buzzing)               

21:02.896 --> 21:04.963
              Carla, it's almost
            midnight-- any sign?

21:05.031 --> 21:06.465
(sighs)                         

21:06.533 --> 21:08.734
Not one                         
blue suede shoe.                

21:08.802 --> 21:12.371
I guess Elvis                   
has disappointed me again.      

21:12.439 --> 21:15.307
         Well, I'm sure the King
    had a lot of other people   

21:15.375 --> 21:17.643
      to visit around the world.

21:20.513 --> 21:22.981
Yeah, well, he isn't            
showing up here                 

21:23.049 --> 21:24.316
or anywhere else tonight.       

21:24.384 --> 21:25.551
(blowing)                       

21:25.618 --> 21:28.687
    Uh, I have flowers          
      for a Miss Tortelli.      

21:28.755 --> 21:30.856
     That's me.                 

21:30.924 --> 21:31.990
Here you go.                    

21:32.058 --> 21:34.660
                     Oh. Thanks.

21:37.931 --> 21:39.198
            "Carla,             

21:39.265 --> 21:41.500
"I wonder if you're             
lonesome tonight.               

21:41.568 --> 21:42.534
The King."                      

21:42.602 --> 21:44.069
                     (gasps)    
Oh, my God.                     

21:44.137 --> 21:45.871
              Oh!               

21:45.939 --> 21:47.206
        I knew it.              

21:47.273 --> 21:48.941
        I knew... I knew        
    he'd come through.          

21:49.009 --> 21:50.409
I knew he wouldn't let me down. 

21:50.477 --> 21:52.578
But just a minute ago, you know,
  you started to doubt that...  

21:52.645 --> 21:54.480
I did not doubt.                
I never doubted.                

21:56.383 --> 21:57.750
I'm going home, Becs.           

21:57.817 --> 21:59.785
I'm going home.                 
I'm gonna stay up all night.    

21:59.853 --> 22:02.654
I'm gonna listen to every record
        Elvis ever made,        

22:02.722 --> 22:04.356
     even "In the Ghetto."      

22:07.627 --> 22:10.229
Uh, Miss Howe, did Miss Tortelli
        get the flowers?        

22:10.296 --> 22:11.497
                Yes, she did.   

22:11.564 --> 22:12.898
            In fact, she just   
              ran up the stairs.
     Ah.                        

22:12.966 --> 22:14.566
      Did you send those?       

22:14.634 --> 22:16.101
          Yes, I did,           

22:16.202 --> 22:18.470
      but those were just       
         for starters.          

22:18.538 --> 22:22.207
This will really push her       
         over the edge.         

22:32.719 --> 22:34.353
        (buzzing)               

22:34.421 --> 22:35.854
         (door opening)         

22:37.290 --> 22:38.657
 Woody, what was that buzzing?  

22:38.725 --> 22:41.293
      Sam, with the razor.      

22:41.361 --> 22:43.996
                 Well, your hair
                 looks the same.

22:44.064 --> 22:46.365
It's the only hair I have left. 

